title: Closed Bearing Block for 1" round unsupported rail

description.text:
This is a closed bearing block for a 1" round, unsupported rail. It is a variant of my open bearing block inspired by WWWektor's contribution. The closed version was created to minimize the springy nature of the open block under the greater pressure of aluminum cutting.
I have not tested this bearing block yet. I will report the performance when I do.

I will be re-working my open bearing block (for a fully supported 3/4" rail) and will upload that model when it is ready for testing.

These blocks use an inexpensive bearing 22mm diameter with 8mm center hub. The rods are cut from 8mm steel rod similar to 3D printer rails. The shaft holes (voids) in the block are for 8mm shafts. The bearing cut-outs are wide enough to add spacer washers on either side of the bearings during installation. There are 2 shafts 75mm and 4 shafts 50mm long. The shaft holes must be drilled to open them just enough to accept the 8mm rods.

I discovered that it was not necessary to use 5/16" nuts and bolts. It just added a lot of code for the hex cutouts and the nuts interfered with the bolt heads when installing the bearings.

Two of these blocks fit into a 3" x 3" (interior dimension) aluminum square tube which is welded to the aluminum gantry sides. The main rail passes through both blocks giving very good strength and no measurable slop.

description.text:
I love the spinner by 2ROBOTGUY. Great size, curved edges, bearing fit snug with no need for glue. The only thing I wanted to do was change the finger pads just a bit. I wanted a little curve in the pad to hold by thumb better and make it a little more ergonomic. Aslo, I found that my finger pads were slipping out so I expanded to post by a tiny bit to make them stick a little better. It does make it necessary to be cautious when inserting the finger pad, there is a weakness in the joint from the post to the pad so when applying the finger pad, make sure your force is centered on the post to prevent breakage. Once applied, it sits snug and won't fall out of it's own accord.

Use supports so you can print the finger pads upright. It uses a little more plastic than 2ROBOTGUY's but I like the feel. Have fun fidgeting. Once again, shout out to 2ROBOTGUY for the original design.

I also tweaked the fingerpads a bit. I found that my original design was flimsy and would often break when installing. The version 13 is a little tougher thought he curve isn't quite as deep.

Printed mine on an Ultimaker 2 using Taulman 645 nylon. I have had good success printing on 3M blue painter's tape with a cold bed and a head temperature of 245C, single layer (continuous Z aka "Joris"), layer thickness 0.1mm. The nylon is extremely flexible, especially when it's this thin and with all these large radii, so it can stretch quite a bit. Haven't tried this particular one in PLA, I imagine it would work fine but just be more stiff.  
The twisted version has a 10-degree twist. I printed it at 0.2mm layer height. This one was much harder to remove from its base for some reason, not sure if it's due to the twist or the layer thickness difference. description.text:
Yet another version of my dock mounted cartridge holder for the Nintendo Switch - this time 4 slot. It is locked into place by the door on the back of the original Switch dock - since the door makes a great snap in mounting point.

Designed to print on most printers without any support in the default file orientation, I don't think it would print well rotated from the default orientation without a lot of post processing. Your printer will need to be able to handle prints ~130mm tall.

To attach this holder to the dock, you will need to align the semi circular cutouts with the protruding tabs on the back edge of the dock door.

I've included 2 versions in this file, the original version with square top corners which I've printed in the photo, and another with rounded top corners (my preference for this dock as it mimics the rounded corners of the switch, but silly me forgot to include them before I printed!).

With around 5% infill, 0.4 nozzle and moderately fast print settings in S3D - the print took me around 1 hour 39 mins with a Folger FT5.

Disclaimer: please use at your own risk - I take no responsibility for this thing scratching your switch dock, setting your house of fire, or your kids/pets turning this into an easy access all you can eat Switch cartridge buffet.

comments.text: I recently broke my original thermistor and swapped it out for the one on my E3D (snipped and soldered), and so far everything is fine. As far as I understand it, the thermistor in the E3D and the stock hotend are just regular 100k ohm thermistors.
comments.author: Bandanam4n

comments.text: While I'm happy that you were able to solder in a new thermistor and it works, I caution everyone as just because they are 100k ohm thermistors, does not mean they perform similarly. The 100k refers to the resistance at some base temperature (probably room temperature, but that could vary from place to place as well) and from there, if the resistor (Thermistor) isn't made of the same material, shape, etc, the temperature->resistance curve could be significantly different, throwing off your results. That's why in marlin you have a large table of "100k thermistors" to choose from, because just because they're 100k doesn't mean their resistance->temperature varies identically at all.

comments.text: BTW  it looks to me that some have had decent luck using this mount (which I printed on my Flux Delta+) and one of the Fang mods that allow use of the stock part blower fan. comments.text: So: I've reflashed my board by doing a cobbled together version of the guides online on how to flash other boards combined with pin outs etc etc using a raspberry pi. Reflashing the board requires an additional programmer (Arduino, pi, etc) and a slight bit of knowledge to load the bootloader. Once flashed, it's easy to re-flash. Will the machine work without a re-flash? Yes. Will it work well? Maybe if Calibrated to a custom displayed vs real temp. I'm talking about situations where it reads 230c but it's actually 215 c, but when it reads 250c it's actually 255c. The reason I upgrade to e3d hotends is consistency. If you want to manually tune every time without knowing the true relative temperatures, that's up to you.

I have used the Reelight LED bicycle lights for several years. The first set of magnets rusted away. Luckily I had a couple of magnets.  
The two arcs are supposed to bend around the wheel spokes, and the magnets are placed inside the hollow cavity during printing. See Instructions.

You must insert the magnets during printing.
  • Hit the PAUSE button.
  • Get the current position with M114.
  • Retract filament and move extruder away with a G1.
  • Carefully insert the magnets.
  • Move extruder back at wind filament forward with a G1 and the XYZ position from step 2.
  • Resume printing.
    • You might need to reheat it to soften the plastic, so you can bend it.

Here are parametric openSCAD files that create chairs and tables.  Objects from a few millimeters across to full size chairs and tables can be built.  The programs are probably best suited for making small models for dioramas. More amusing than useful perhaps but it is interesting to quickly construct a succession of different tables and chairs. For example the chair can be widened to make a bench or lengthened to make a bed.
You need openSCAD to make full use of the parametric files.  OpenSCAD is easy to download and install.  It includes an editor that can be used to vary the input parameters in the scad files.
For the table:
There are 5 settable parameters; 3 are the length, width, and depth of the top.  The legs are square in cross section and the side length of the square and the length of the leg are the 2 additional variables.
For the chair:
There are 9 settable parameters. The table forms the seat and legs of the chair so 5 of the variables are the same as the variables for the table.  The back of the chair has three vertical members and two horizontal members.  Two variables set the width of these members.  The final two parameters set the height of the chair back and the height of the legs that connect to the seat of the chair.  Actually the chair back has two additional parameters but they are constrained by the values used for the seat.
Four stl files are provided: chair.stl, bench.stl, bed,stl and table.stl.  Printed versions are shown in the image at the upper left.
Two parametric scad files are included: chair.scad and table.scad.  Parameters for bench.stl and bed.stl are included as comments at the end of chair.scad.

The top of the table lies flat on the build surface.  Print without support to get a nice shiny table top.
The chair, bench, and bed sit upright on the build surface.  Printed on rafts the bench and bed have a noticeable sag.  The chair has a slight sag which looks natural.  Print the bench and bed with external support to get flat surfaces.

title: Skyrim Dwemer Mace
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Let's face it, who hasn't day-dreamed of wandering the tundra of Skyrim, searching for treasure, and fighting dragons? Well with this replica Dwemer Mace, you can be one step closer to achieving your Dovakiin adventurer status!

This is a 5-part print, so be sure to download all files available. There are assembly instructions below, because additional hardware is required. These model pieces were made with a 6" cubic build area in mind, and should fit accordingly. The assembled prop is approximately 18" in total length.

Printer Brand:

Printrbot

Printer:

Printrbot Simple Metal

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

10%

Notes:

I used both rafts and supports to print these parts, but you may use your discretion based on your printer settings. I would recommend printing everything vertically as to avoid any unnecessary support clean-up. I also printed the Mace Head upside-down to make things a bit easier on myself. It was about a 15 hour print, so find something fun to fill the time, like spelunking into an undiscovered Dwemer ruin.

I used Matter Control for my slicing software and was able to print all pieces at full scale. I would not recommend scaling down the model pieces, as the through holes and hex nut insets were intended to be used at full scale. If the pieces are scaled up or down, the tolerances will change, therefore making the associated hardware unusable.

Assembly

This build will require a trip to your local hardware store. You will need (2) 1/2"-13 Hex Nuts and a corresponding 18" long 1/2"-13 threaded rod (which you will need to cut to length accordingly).

There will be support material within the hex nut sockets. Clean them out well and the nuts will fit in just fine. To secure the nuts in place, I used medium strength 2-part epoxy. I also used thread-locker to ensure the end caps won't become loose while handling the finished prop.

Paint Finish

For this project I decided to use Bondo to fill in the ridges left by the printing process, then used many files and sandpaper grits to sand it smooth. I used a couple of base coats of primer, then a hammered paint to add texture. Top coat of bright gold, then a wash of raw umber acrylic, sealed with a crystal clear.

All the spray paints / clears I use are by Krylon. I find the primers sand very well, and the paints adhere to most any surfaces. Of course, you can finish this model however you'd like, this is just what I used.

comments.text: Hey bud, a tip on those waves near holes and corners: Those can form as printers get older, the belts loosen, the rail brackets fatigue, and some printers even have it by default. Its a case by case scenario but its linked to acceleration and jerk settings in conjunction with its mechanical state. In different printers, theres always a different resonance frequency. Your particular settings are in disagreement with it. There is a workaround. As the extruder rounds a corner, it cant just go from 0-50mm/s instantly, it would skip, so we made a simple but elegant solution to it. Tell the firmware that the speed change as it rounds a corner can not be more than (X.XX mm/s). So if your jerk is 20, when it goes around a corner, the speed change in any direction is 20mm/s and no more. Once it exits the corner and speed change (jerk) initiates, acceleration kicks in to bring it up to its set speed (because 20mm/s to 50mm.s instantly, wont work either), so that it doesnt skip after the corner either. Acceleration is a difficult value to get right, but we'll go into that. Its just a math problem, but in order to pick a number, you need to know what speed you will be printing at; there is a speed for extruder steppers themselves, travel moves, and path extrusion moves, each axis has a setting. These waves happen because the acceleration is too high for what the belt, frame, or axis can handle. Its basically whiplash, which is a term we dont hear as much these days. You accelerate too fast and the belt has to catch up, then because its working as a rubber band at that time, it overshoots, and the overshoot is where the high peak of the wave forms. If you look top down on them, you should see thick in thin areas, rather than wavy areas. If its waving, thats axis or extruder wobble and thats a mechanical problem. Today we will focus on the former.

description.text: Make your own slides on any dimension aluminum extrusion.  This slide is simple to print, and easy to assemble.  It uses a combination of printed slide surfaces and RC car bearings for very low friction. Use a pair of them with your carriage. I am running them on my Pocket Printer with good results.

Print in pla, which has very good wear characteristics.  You may need to make some adjustments to the dimension of the printed slide surfaces to get the fit you desire.  The dimensions between the bearings is 0.2 mm less than the extrusion width.  The slide flexes slightly to give a preload to the bearings.  You can adjust for you own preferences.
See the pdf assembly drawing for critical dimensions and instructions.  There is also an exploded view of an application on the Pocket Printer page.
Use 623ZZ bearings (3 x 10 x 4), you can get a 10 pack for under $10.  You also need M3 x 20 screws and 3 mm washers.

Eccentric spacers are used for preloading the tension on the wheels.
You can get the ball studs from me for $1 each, and I also precisely build the carbon fiber, zero-backlash, magnetic arms. My website is http://www.MagBallArms.com

This design works nicely with my effector which sports an LED light ring and 3 PLA cooling fans: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1546124

http://openbuildspartstore.com/aluminum-spacers/ (choose 1/4")
http://openbuildspartstore.com/eccentric-spacer/ (choose 1/4")

Per carriage, you will need:
3 of the above V- or W-wheels.
2 of the above 1/4" spacers (or you could use 6mm).
1 of the above 1/4" eccentric spacers (or you could use 6mm).
3 M5x35 bolts.
1 large M5 washer for the top side of the eccentric spacer (optional).
3 M5 nylock nuts to secure the three axles.
2 3/8" ball studs.

2 M3x35 SHCS for the tightener.
2 M3 nuts for the tightener.

If your belts are farther above your carriages, you can easily adapt by using a longer M3 vertical screw.

The belt tightener this uses is very simple and easy to adjust with two M3x35 screws.
I found that this delivered better results than using zip ties. My prints got more accurate by about 50 microns.

title: 2020 Carriages for Magnetic Arms and Mini V-Wheels

description.text:
These carriages work for 2020 aluminum extrusions and 15mm diameter V-wheels, such as the ones from OpenBuilds or RobotDigg.com.
A horizontal M3x35 screw is used for preloading the tension on the wheels.
You can get the ball studs from me for $1 each, and I also precisely build the carbon fiber, zero-backlash, magnetic arms. My website is http://www.MagBallArms.com

This design works nicely with my effector which sports an LED light ring and 3 PLA cooling fans: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1546124

Here are links to the mini V-wheels from RobotDigg:
http://www.robotdigg.com/product/519/Delrin-Guide-Bearing-Kit

Here are links to the mini V-wheels from OpenBuilds:
http://openbuildspartstore.com/delrin-mini-v-wheel-kit/

Per carriage, you will need:
3 of the above V-wheels.
3 M5x25 bolts.
3 M5 nylock nuts to secure the three axles.
2 3/8" ball studs (from me).
2 M3 nylock nuts to secure the ball studs.
2 M3x35 SHCS for the belt tightener.
2 M3 nuts for the belt tightener.
1 M3x35 SHCS for preloading the carriage wheels.
1 M3 nylock nut for preloading the carriage wheels.
1 M3x20 SHCS for the vertical post for the upper G2 belt attachment.
1 M3 nut to secure the vertical post.

You can easily alter the OpenSCAD source to make this work with 2040 or 2060 extrusions, by changing the value for extrusionWidth from 20.0mm to 40.0 or 60.0mm.

If your belts are farther above your carriages, you can easily adapt by using a longer M3 vertical screw.

The belt tightener this uses is very simple and easy to adjust with two M3x35 screws.
I found that this delivered better results than using zip ties. My prints got more accurate by about 50 microns.

I also have a version for 24mm diameter V-wheels: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2183347

Note: there needs to be a tiny shim between the aluminum spacers and the mini V-wheels, otherwise the aluminum spacers rub against the bearings.

I've design and tested carriages using both 15mm mini V-wheels and 24mm V-wheels, and I prefer the 24mm versions. Bigger wheels roll better and the shims aren't needed.

description.text:
Universal Derailleur Actuator for bicycles:

This super strong servo actuator fits most bottle holder mounts and can therefore be attached to almost every bicycle frame. Many frames have two bottle holder mounts, so it is possible to drive both front and rear derailleur.

I recommend to use the gearmotor with 6 to 10 rpm and 6V supply voltage. The shown motor (very high torque) is self-locking type, therefore there is absolutely no current consumption during standby.
Furthermore a 5kOhm potentiometre will be required. In this way it is possible to use a circuit board of an old RC servo motor to control the unit (6V type!!) with a PWM-signal (e.g. Arduino).

Use this actuator to automate gear shifting process on your bicycle based on wheel or crank speed.
Print with transparent red filament and attach an LED (hole below gear motor for 5mm LED type) to use unit also as a safety feature for cycling at night.

description.text:
I've never been into tops, but after seeing the high-tech tops on the Internet costing upwards of $1000, it brings new interest for high-tech kid toys.

This top was designed after designing and making some roller-nearing spinner toys for my daughter. This top is the next thing.

Tops that wobble and turn about 20 times and fall are no fun. Correct me if I'm mistaken but the key to a long-spinning top is stability. We're not talking about a $1000 top that is CNC turned on a lathe but 3D printed from plastic, where is hardly any weight, so stability comes with added weights. The heavier the weights are, the more momentum it will have. Keeping the weight low will lower the center of gravity which improves stability.

This top was designed to take 6 3/8" nuts, and a 1/4" ball bearing on the bottom.
The key to this top is balancing the nuts to keep weight as evenly distributed as possible. Each nut varies slightly in size and weight so it's important to weigh them individually.

Obviously, the higher the precision, the nicer the part will turn out. I would recommend using a standard PLA, since pressing the nuts into the top may crack it. Don't ask me how I know this. This is the second one I've printed, with transparent aqua PLA. The previous top I've printed was a standard PLA and turned out great, without cracking. Perhaps soaking the top in hot water before pressing may help softening the PLA, but when the plastic cools, it might crack under stress. I haven't tried it - just a suggestion.

I printed my tops with 3 shells and 15% infill, but it doesn't matter too much.

Enjoy.
